<span id="freeTextContainer9367497945715201677">The Piketty of the noughties - i.e. it&apos;s a bestselling forest of empirical detail, with lots of methodological problems and ideological overinterpretation. I was very impressed, as an undergrad with the same axe to grind as the authors.<br/><br/>How does it hold up after ten years? Well, we&apos;ve learned what a forest (or <a href='http://www.stat.columbia.edu/~gelman/research/unpublished/p_hacking.pdf' rel='nofollow noopener'>garden</a>) of empirical detail sadly often means: data dredging, cherry-picking, p-hacking and so on.<br/><br/><a href='https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/m/pubmed/15016244/' rel='nofollow noopener'>Here&apos;s a meta-analysis</a> contradicting the health thesis, from 2004.<br/><br/>Here&apos;s the excellent anal</span>
  <span id="freeText9367497945715201677" style="display:none">The Piketty of the noughties - i.e. it's a bestselling forest of empirical detail, with lots of methodological problems and ideological overinterpretation. I was very impressed, as an undergrad with the same axe to grind as the authors.<br /><br />How does it hold up after ten years? Well, we've learned what a forest (or <a href="http://www.stat.columbia.edu/~gelman/research/unpublished/p_hacking.pdf" rel="nofollow noopener">garden</a>) of empirical detail sadly often means: data dredging, cherry-picking, p-hacking and so on.<br /><br /><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/m/pubmed/15016244/" rel="nofollow noopener">Here's a meta-analysis</a> contradicting the health thesis, from 2004.<br /><br />Here's the excellent analyst Nintil <a href="https://nintil.com/2017/06/26/on-the-effects-of-inequality-on-economic-growth/" rel="nofollow noopener">contradicting the growth thesis</a>.<br /><br />Up-to-date critique (from a partisan figure) <a href="https://spiritleveldelusion.blogspot.com/2019/03/the-spirit-level-ten-years-on.html" rel="nofollow noopener">here</a>.</span>
