    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3607395810" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3607395810" />
    <a title="Alexandru" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7856222-alexandru"><img alt="Alexandru" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1329847628p2/7856222.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3607395810?book_show_action=true">Dec 16, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alexandru" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alexandru" href="/user/show/7856222-alexandru">Alexandru</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780241954294" href="/book/show/10076196-the-spirit-level">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3607395810" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11037657378421281560">First of all, I want to make clear from the start that I support the idea that inequality is something that we should solve in any society and I&apos;ve read a number of books on this issue. This one was recommended to me by my Canadian friend we disagreed on the issue. Being born in the URSS my argument, before reading this book, was that inequality is not the First issue, and the way you achieve it is very important. My argument was that USSR before its collapse was having the same equality level a</span>
  <span id="freeText11037657378421281560" style="display:none">First of all, I want to make clear from the start that I support the idea that inequality is something that we should solve in any society and I've read a number of books on this issue. This one was recommended to me by my Canadian friend we disagreed on the issue. Being born in the URSS my argument, before reading this book, was that inequality is not the First issue, and the way you achieve it is very important. My argument was that USSR before its collapse was having the same equality level as the Scandinavian countries today and it was not heaven to live in. So this is how I decided to read the book that my friend was insisting will answer all my questions related to inequality. The main idea of the book is just plain wrong - it says that solving inequality will solve all main issues of human societies - starting from climate change to human health, drug usage, stress, gender equality, and suicide rates - all of these are influenced by a plethora of factors. And the book becomes just ridiculous when it is claiming things that are just impossible taking into account the below-presented ideas. So in my view, the book is a typical example of an ideology driven "science" - the situation when the researcher already has the conclusion before the research even began and this is due to the fact that everything in this book is interpreted in a very one-sided way with too much cherrypicking and ignoring the opposing evidence.<br /><br />I identified 5 main issues with the method used by the authors:<br />1) The fact that only 25 reachest countries were taken into consideration is something that cannot be ignored, even taking into account the explanations of the books authors why this was done. The lack of data is not something that can be used as an excuse and maybe the authors should repeat their research today, after more than 10 years, and see if they still can make the same conclusions and I am sure the results would be very different.<br />2) The graphs the authors used are pictures of countries at a specific moment in time and the issue of inequality should be analyzed in time. For example, Piketty in "Capital" is doing that, again for a limited number of countries, but it clearly shows the tendency and the correlation. It is just absolutely mind-boggling to me why the authors did not even try to do that since the info for the countries they used was available. It would be interesting to see that.<br />3) The domino effect or the cake idea when analyzing complex issues - it is just unacceptable that serious research is not even trying to see if any of the effects of inequality mentioned are influenced by other factors - such as diversity of a society of a country when we speak of trust, or migration when we speak of many issues - gender equality, crime, obesity, and others, or life expectancy can be influenced by culture - like for example the role of suicide in Japan or local cuisine or lifestyle. another defect the book suffers from is the intermingling of effects - for example, the link between stress, poor health, obesity, life expectancy, homicide, happiness, trust are interconnected and one might influence another, so in the end, the authors should just find that the primary effect is inequality and if they would prove it the domino effect would be enough to affirm that all the mentioned ill effects are caused by the primary cause, but unfortunately this was not done at no point. For example, Piketty in his book clearly shows that inequality is reduced seriously during military conflict, especially the world wars, but I doubt that this reduction brought a lot of happiness and longer life for people living in France, UK, Germany, and others affected by this bloody conflict.<br />4) One that was mentioned by many readers - Correlation does not mean Causation. And this is addressed the best by Christopher Snowdon in his book that I still have to read and on his blog where he is speaking about this in detail.<br />5) Cherrypicking - some countries that fulfill the requirements of 50 richest that are proving that the authors are wrong - such as South Korea, Hong Kong, Slovenia, and the Czech Republic- were ignored for some reason. As well on some graphs, the countries that prove the opposite effect are conveniently left behind - in the majority cases, these are Japan, Singapore, Israel, etc.<br /><br />The only truthful idea for which I awarded 2 stars instead of 1 to this book is the idea that Homo Sapiens are psychologically happier when everyone is equal. This is by the way valid not only for us but for many mammals - for example, the famous experiment on monkeys and the banana vs cucumber effect on monkeys doing the same tasks. In fact, in our culture we have a joke about this correlation that is explaining this point fairly well:<br />"Once God visited a village with hard-working and kind-hearted farmers living in a close-knitted community and decided to reward the most hard-working farmers that were neighbors by granting them any wish they desire. So he is approaching the first farmer and telling him - I will grant you any wish but with one condition - your neighbor will get double of what you will get (so if you will ask for one cow, the neighbor will get two). The farmer without hesitation replied to God - please remove one of my eyes." So, yes social hierarchy is a part of our human nature, and mating is influenced by it since it is one of the most important factors for women when choosing a life partner. Not sure it will be easy to change that quickly and without pain.<br /><br />Another idea that deserves attention is at the end of the book speaking about employees' participation in corporate governance structures.<br /><br />In conclusion, this book was targeting developed countries readers since it is only speaking about the US, UK, and English speaking countries, leaving behind the rest. The idea of equality is a great one, but it becomes relevant the moment a country is more or less successful in fighting off corruption and poverty because a post-war country might reach absolute equality, but it will definitively not be doing better than an unequal peaceful country. As well the price you pay for reaching equality is important and probably even for the developed countries this is one the biggest debates - how we reach this better version of society.</span>
  <a data-text-id="11037657378421281560" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


